                  "arguments": "{\"path\":\"/tmp/isolated_workspace_1091/report.md\",\"content\":\"# Homework Report: Projective Geometry Proofs and SIFT Programming Experiment\\n\\n## 1. Written Assignment: Projective Geometry and Perspective Projection\\n\\n### 1.1 Perspective projection model\\n\\nAssume the camera center is the origin\\n\\n\\\\[\\nO=(0,0,0),\\n\\\\]\\n\\nand the image plane is\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\Pi_i: z=-f,\\\\qquad f>0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nFor a spatial point\\n\\n\\\\[\\nP=(X,Y,Z),\\\\qquad Z\\\\neq 0,\\n\\\\]\\n\\nthe ray from the origin through \\\\(P\\\\) is\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\ell(\\\\lambda)=\\\\lambda(X,Y,Z),\\\\qquad \\\\lambda\\\\in\\\\mathbb R.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nIts intersection with the image plane satisfies\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\lambda Z=-f \\\\quad\\\\Longrightarrow\\\\quad \\\\lambda=-\\\\frac{f}{Z}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nHence the perspective image point is\\n\\n\\\\[\\np=(x,y,-f)=\\\\left(-\\\\frac{fX}{Z},-\\\\frac{fY}{Z},-f\\\\right).\\n\\\\]\\n\\nUsually we keep only the image coordinates:\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{x=-\\\\frac{fX}{Z},\\\\qquad y=-\\\\frac{fY}{Z}}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThis is the standard central-projection model used in the homework.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1.2 Proof that a circle parallel to the image plane projects to a circle\\n\\nSuppose a circle lies in the plane\\n\\n\\\\[\\nZ=Z_0,\\n\\\\]\\n\\nwhere \\\\(Z_0\\\\) is a constant. Since this plane is parallel to the image plane \\\\(z=-f\\\\), every point on the circle has the same depth.\\n\\nLet the circle in 3D be centered at\\n\\n\\\\[\\nC=(X_0,Y_0,Z_0)\\n\\\\]\\n\\nwith radius \\\\(R\\\\). Its equation is\\n\\n\\\\[\\n(X-X_0)^2+(Y-Y_0)^2=R^2,\\\\qquad Z=Z_0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nUnder perspective projection,\\n\\n\\\\[\\nx=-\\\\frac{fX}{Z_0},\\n\\\\qquad\\ny=-\\\\frac{fY}{Z_0}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSo equivalently,\\n\\n\\\\[\\nX=-\\\\frac{Z_0}{f}x,\\n\\\\qquad\\nY=-\\\\frac{Z_0}{f}y.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSubstitute these into the circle equation:\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\left(-\\\\frac{Z_0}{f}x-X_0\\\\right)^2+\\n\\\\left(-\\\\frac{Z_0}{f}y-Y_0\\\\right)^2=R^2.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nRewrite each term by factoring \\\\(-Z_0/f\\\\):\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\left(-\\\\frac{Z_0}{f}\\\\right)^2\\n\\\\left(x+\\\\frac{fX_0}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2+\\n\\\\left(-\\\\frac{Z_0}{f}\\\\right)^2\\n\\\\left(y+\\\\frac{fY_0}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2=R^2.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSince \\\\((-Z_0/f)^2=Z_0^2/f^2\\\\), we get\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\frac{Z_0^2}{f^2}\\n\\\\left[\\n\\\\left(x+\\\\frac{fX_0}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2+\\n\\\\left(y+\\\\frac{fY_0}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2\\n\\\\right]=R^2.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nMultiply both sides by \\\\(f^2/Z_0^2\\\\):\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\left(x+\\\\frac{fX_0}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2+\\n\\\\left(y+\\\\frac{fY_0}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2\\n=\\n\\\\left(\\\\frac{fR}{Z_0}\\\\right)^2.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nDefine the image-center coordinates and image radius by\\n\\n\\\\[\\n x_c=-\\\\frac{fX_0}{Z_0},\\n \\\\qquad\\n y_c=-\\\\frac{fY_0}{Z_0},\\n \\\\qquad\\n r=\\\\frac{fR}{|Z_0|}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThen the projected curve becomes\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{(x-x_c)^2+(y-y_c)^2=r^2.}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSo a circle in any plane parallel to the image plane remains a circle after projection.\\n\\n#### Why this happens\\nThe essential reason is that all points of the original circle share the same depth \\\\(Z_0\\\\). Therefore the perspective mapping reduces to a uniform scaling in both \\\\(X\\\\) and \\\\(Y\\\\) directions plus a translation of the center. Uniform scaling preserves the class of circles.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1.3 Vanishing point of a family of parallel lines lying on a plane\\n\\nConsider the plane\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\Pi: AX+BY+CZ+D=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nTake a family of lines on this plane that are all parallel to the direction vector\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\mathbf d=(l,m,n).\\n\\\\]\\n\\nBecause each such line lies on \\\\(\\\\Pi\\\\), its direction must be parallel to the plane, so\\n\\n\\\\[\\nA l + B m + C n =0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nPick any point \\\\(P_0=(X_0,Y_0,Z_0)\\\\) on one of the lines. That line can be written as\\n\\n\\\\[\\nP(t)=P_0+t\\\\mathbf d=(X_0+tl,\\\\ Y_0+tm,\\\\ Z_0+tn).\\n\\\\]\\n\\nIts image coordinates are\\n\\n\\\\[\\nx(t)=-f\\\\frac{X_0+tl}{Z_0+tn},\\n\\\\qquad\\ny(t)=-f\\\\frac{Y_0+tm}{Z_0+tn}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThe vanishing point is the limit as \\\\(t\\\\to\\\\infty\\\\):\\n\\n\\\\[\\nx_v=\\n\\\\lim_{t\\\\to\\\\infty}-f\\\\frac{X_0+tl}{Z_0+tn}\\n=-f\\\\frac{l}{n},\\n\\\\qquad\\ny_v=\\n\\\\lim_{t\\\\to\\\\infty}-f\\\\frac{Y_0+tm}{Z_0+tn}\\n=-f\\\\frac{m}{n},\\n\\\\]\\n\\nprovided \\\\(n\\\\neq 0\\\\). Therefore\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{(x_v,y_v)=\\\\left(-f\\\\frac{l}{n},-f\\\\frac{m}{n}\\\\right).}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThis formula depends only on the direction vector and not on the particular line chosen. That is exactly why parallel lines meet at one common vanishing point in the image.\\n\\n#### Special note when \\\\(n=0\\\\)\\nIf \\\\(n=0\\\\), the line direction is parallel to the image plane, and the limit goes to infinity. Geometrically, the vanishing point is an ideal point at infinity, which is also consistent with projective geometry.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1.4 Proof that all such vanishing points are collinear\\n\\nNow consider **all** possible line directions \\\\(\\\\mathbf d=(l,m,n)\\\\) lying in the plane \\\\(\\\\Pi\\\\). They satisfy\\n\\n\\\\[\\nAl+Bm+Cn=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nFor each direction with \\\\(n\\\\neq 0\\\\), the vanishing point is\\n\\n\\\\[\\nx_v=-f\\\\frac{l}{n},\\n\\\\qquad\\ny_v=-f\\\\frac{m}{n}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nEquivalently,\\n\\n\\\\[\\nl=-\\\\frac{n}{f}x_v,\\n\\\\qquad\\nm=-\\\\frac{n}{f}y_v.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSubstitute into the plane-parallel condition:\\n\\n\\\\[\\nA\\\\left(-\\\\frac{n}{f}x_v\\\\right)+B\\\\left(-\\\\frac{n}{f}y_v\\\\right)+Cn=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nFactor out \\\\(n\\\\):\\n\\n\\\\[\\nn\\\\left(-\\\\frac{Ax_v+By_v}{f}+C\\\\right)=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSince \\\\(n\\\\neq 0\\\\),\\n\\n\\\\[\\n-\\\\frac{Ax_v+By_v}{f}+C=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nMultiply by \\\\(f\\\\):\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{Ax_v+By_v-Cf=0.}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nIf the homework uses the opposite sign convention for the image plane or projection formula, the line may also be written equivalently as\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{Ax_v+By_v+Cf=0.}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThe difference is purely due to coordinate-sign convention. Under the convention adopted in this report, where the image plane is \\\\(z=-f\\\\) and \\\\(x=-fX/Z, y=-fY/Z\\\\), the derived equation is\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{Ax_v+By_v-Cf=0.}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThus all vanishing points of directions contained in the plane lie on a single image line, namely the **vanishing line** (or horizon line) of the plane.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1.5 Geometric interpretation of the vanishing line\\n\\nThe vanishing line is the image of the line at infinity of the plane \\\\(\\\\Pi\\\\). In Euclidean geometry, parallel lines never intersect; in projective geometry, they intersect at ideal points. All ideal points of directions lying in one plane form a line at infinity on that plane, and perspective projection maps that line to an ordinary line in the image.\\n\\nSo the statement “all vanishing points are collinear” is not accidental; it is a direct consequence of the preservation of incidence under projective mapping.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1.6 Verification by special cases\\n\\n#### Case 1: plane \\\\(Y=0\\\\)\\nHere\\n\\n\\\\[\\nA=0,\\\\quad B=1,\\\\quad C=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThe vanishing-line equation becomes\\n\\n\\\\[\\n0\\\\cdot x_v + 1\\\\cdot y_v - 0\\\\cdot f = 0\\n\\\\quad\\\\Longrightarrow\\\\quad\\n\\\\boxed{y_v=0.}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThis is correct: all directions lying in the plane \\\\(Y=0\\\\) have image vanishing points on the image \\\\(x\\\\)-axis.\\n\\n#### Case 2: plane \\\\(X=0\\\\)\\nHere\\n\\n\\\\[\\nA=1,\\\\quad B=0,\\\\quad C=0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThen\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\boxed{x_v=0.}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSo all vanishing points lie on the image \\\\(y\\\\)-axis, exactly as expected.\\n\\n#### Case 3: plane \\\\(Z=Z_1\\\\), parallel to the image plane\\nA plane parallel to the image plane has normal vector \\\\((0,0,1)\\\\), so\\n\\n\\\\[\\nA=0,\\\\quad B=0,\\\\quad C=1.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThe equation becomes\\n\\n\\\\[\\n-f=0,\\n\\\\]\\n\\nwhich has no finite solution. This means all vanishing points are at infinity, matching the fact that lines on a plane parallel to the image plane remain parallel in the image.\\n\\n#### Case 4: horizontal ground plane\\nSuppose the plane is\\n\\n\\\\[\\nZ=h.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nAgain it is parallel to the image plane under this coordinate model, so its vanishing line is at infinity. This is another useful consistency check.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1.7 Summary of the written assignment\\n\\nUnder the perspective model\\n\\n\\\\[\\nx=-\\\\frac{fX}{Z},\\\\qquad y=-\\\\frac{fY}{Z},\\n\\\\]\\n\\nwe proved:\\n\\n1. A circle in a plane parallel to the image plane projects to a circle:\\n   \\\\[\\n   (x-x_c)^2+(y-y_c)^2=r^2.\\n   \\\\]\\n2. The vanishing point of lines with direction \\\\((l,m,n)\\\\) is\\n   \\\\[\\n   (x_v,y_v)=\\\\left(-f\\\\frac{l}{n},-f\\\\frac{m}{n}\\\\right).\\n   \\\\]\\n3. If those directions lie in plane \\\\(AX+BY+CZ+D=0\\\\), then all vanishing points are collinear and form the vanishing line:\\n   \\\\[\\n   Ax_v+By_v-Cf=0\\n   \\\\]\\n   (or equivalently \\\\(Ax_v+By_v+Cf=0\\\\) under the alternative sign convention).\\n\\nThese results are standard but fundamental conclusions of projective geometry and perspective imaging.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Programming Assignment: SIFT Experiment Report\\n\\n### 2.1 Experimental goal\\n\\nThe goal of this programming task is to implement the main stages of SIFT (Scale-Invariant Feature Transform) and explain the role of each component:\\n\\n1. multi-scale Gaussian pyramid construction;\\n2. Difference of Gaussian (DoG) extrema detection;\\n3. low-contrast rejection and edge-response suppression;\\n4. dominant orientation assignment;\\n5. 128-dimensional descriptor construction.\\n\\nThe provided `sift.py` already gives the required pipeline skeleton, including:\\n\\n- grayscale normalization,\\n- Gaussian blur wrapper,\\n- Sobel gradient computation,\\n- keypoint/orientation/descriptor interfaces,\\n- output visualization `sift_keypoints_vis.png`.\\n\\nSo the report focuses on the algorithmic design and the expected behavior of the implementation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.2 Why DoG approximates LoG\\n\\nA core idea in SIFT is to search for stable extrema in scale space. The ideal operator is the **scale-normalized Laplacian of Gaussian**:\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\sigma^2 \\\\nabla^2 G(x,y,\\\\sigma).\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThis operator is theoretically attractive because blob-like structures achieve extrema at characteristic scales. However, computing LoG directly at many scales is relatively expensive.\\n\\nSIFT instead uses the Difference of Gaussian:\\n\\n\\\\[\\nD(x,y,\\\\sigma)=L(x,y,k\\\\sigma)-L(x,y,\\\\sigma),\\n\\\\]\\n\\nwhere\\n\\n\\\\[\\nL(x,y,\\\\sigma)=G(x,y,\\\\sigma) * I(x,y).\\n\\\\]\\n\\nUsing a first-order Taylor expansion in scale,\\n\\n\\\\[\\nL(x,y,k\\\\sigma)-L(x,y,\\\\sigma)\\n\\\\approx (k-1)\\\\sigma\\\\frac{\\\\partial L}{\\\\partial \\\\sigma}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nFrom scale-space theory,\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\sigma \\\\frac{\\\\partial L}{\\\\partial \\\\sigma}=\\\\sigma^2 \\\\nabla^2 L.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nTherefore,\\n\\n\\\\[\\nD(x,y,\\\\sigma)\\n\\\\approx (k-1)\\\\sigma^2\\\\nabla^2 L(x,y,\\\\sigma).\\n\\\\]\\n\\nSo DoG is proportional to the scale-normalized LoG up to a constant factor. This means the locations of extrema are nearly the same, while the computation is much cheaper because DoG only requires subtracting adjacent Gaussian images.\\n\\n#### Efficiency advantage\\n- Gaussian blurring is separable and can be computed efficiently.\\n- Once the Gaussian pyramid is built, DoG images are obtained by simple subtraction.\\n- This avoids explicitly filtering each scale by the second-order LoG kernel.\\n\\nThat is the main reason DoG became the practical choice in SIFT.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.3 Gaussian pyramid and octave structure\\n\\nA standard SIFT implementation builds a Gaussian pyramid organized by **octaves** and **scales**.\\n\\n- Within one octave, the image is repeatedly blurred with increasing \\\\(\\\\sigma\\\\).\\n- After enough blur levels are generated, the image is downsampled by a factor of 2 to start the next octave.\\n- If each octave contains \\\\(s\\\\) effective intervals, one usually stores \\\\(s+3\\\\) Gaussian images so that \\\\(s+2\\\\) DoG images are available.\\n\\nIn the code skeleton:\\n\\n```python\\nbuild_gaussian_pyramid(image, sigma_base=1.6, num_octaves=4, num_scales=3)\\n```\\n\\nthis corresponds to the classical design with\\n\\n\\\\[\\nk=2^{1/s}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThe absolute scale in each octave increases geometrically:\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\sigma_i = \\\\sigma_0 k^i.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThis construction gives dense sampling in scale while keeping computation manageable.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.4 3x3x3 extrema detection in DoG space\\n\\nFor each interior DoG image, every pixel is compared with its 26 neighbors in the 3D neighborhood:\\n\\n- 9 pixels in the previous scale,\\n- 8 neighboring pixels in the current scale (excluding itself),\\n- 9 pixels in the next scale.\\n\\nA candidate is kept only if it is strictly larger than all neighbors (local maximum) or strictly smaller than all neighbors (local minimum).\\n\\nThis is why the method is often called **3x3x3 extrema detection**.\\n\\n#### Why this step matters\\nA SIFT keypoint must be stable both spatially and across scale. A corner may be strong in the image plane but unstable under blur; conversely, some structures only become clear at a certain scale. The 3D search solves both issues at once.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.5 Contrast thresholding\\n\\nNot every DoG extremum is meaningful. Weak responses often come from noise, quantization, or insignificant texture. Therefore SIFT removes points whose DoG magnitude is too small:\\n\\n\\\\[\\n|D(x,y,\\\\sigma)| < T_c.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nIn practical code this appears as a `contrast_thresh`, for example the skeleton uses:\\n\\n```python\\ncontrast_thresh = 0.03\\n```\\n\\nA larger threshold keeps fewer but more stable keypoints; a smaller threshold keeps more points but increases sensitivity to noise.\\n\\n#### Interpretation\\nThe DoG value estimates local intensity variation after band-pass filtering in scale space. If that value is close to zero, the point is usually not distinctive enough for matching.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.6 Hessian-based edge response suppression\\n\\nDoG extrema often occur on elongated edges. Edge points are unstable because small shifts perpendicular to the edge change the location dramatically, while motion along the edge is ambiguous.\\n\\nTo reject these points, SIFT examines the Hessian matrix at the candidate:\\n\\n\\\\[\\nH=\\n\\\\begin{bmatrix}\\nD_{xx} & D_{xy} \\\\\\\\\\nD_{xy} & D_{yy}\\n\\\\end{bmatrix}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nLet its eigenvalues be \\\\(\\\\alpha\\\\ge \\\\beta>0\\\\). For an edge-like response, the ratio \\\\(\\\\alpha/\\\\beta\\\\) is large. Instead of explicitly computing eigenvalues, SIFT uses\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\frac{(\\\\operatorname{Tr}H)^2}{\\\\det H}\\n=\\n\\\\frac{(\\\\alpha+\\\\beta)^2}{\\\\alpha\\\\beta}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nIf\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\frac{\\\\alpha}{\\\\beta}=r,\\n\\\\]\\n\\nthen the expression becomes\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\frac{(r+1)^2}{r}.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nHence the rejection rule is\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\frac{(\\\\operatorname{Tr}H)^2}{\\\\det H} < \\\\frac{(r+1)^2}{r},\\n\\\\qquad \\\\det H>0.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThe code skeleton uses\\n\\n```python\\nedge_r = 10.0\\n```\\n\\nwhich corresponds to the classical Lowe setting.\\n\\n#### Effect\\n- corners and blob-like structures are preserved;\\n- ridge/edge responses are removed;\\n- resulting keypoints are more repeatable and more useful for matching.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.7 Orientation assignment\\n\\nAfter keypoint detection, SIFT assigns one or more canonical orientations so that the descriptor becomes rotation invariant.\\n\\nFor each keypoint \\\\((x,y,\\\\sigma)\\\\):\\n\\n1. compute gradients in a neighborhood around the keypoint;\\n2. weight each sample by a Gaussian window with\\n   \\\\[\\n   \\\\sigma_{\\\\text{ori}} = 1.5\\\\sigma;\\n   \\\\]\\n3. vote into a 36-bin orientation histogram over \\\\([0,2\\\\pi)\\\\);\\n4. smooth the histogram;\\n5. detect peaks; any peak at least \\\\(0.8\\\\) times the global maximum generates a valid orientation.\\n\\nThis means a single spatial keypoint may create multiple oriented keypoints if the local structure contains several dominant directions.\\n\\n#### Why histogram smoothing is useful\\nRaw gradient histograms are noisy because gradient directions are discrete and image intensities are sampled on a grid. Smoothing suppresses accidental fluctuations and makes the dominant orientation more stable.\\n\\n#### Why parabolic interpolation is used\\nThe strongest orientation rarely lies exactly at the center of a discrete histogram bin. Let the peak bin be surrounded by left and right neighbors. A quadratic fit through the three values gives a sub-bin estimate of the peak location. This improves orientation precision and therefore improves descriptor alignment.\\n\\nIn short:\\n- smoothing improves robustness,\\n- parabolic interpolation improves accuracy.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.8 Construction of the 128-D descriptor\\n\\nThe SIFT descriptor is built from a local patch around the oriented keypoint.\\n\\n#### Step 1: choose a 16x16 support region\\nA square neighborhood centered at the keypoint is sampled. In the standard design, it corresponds to a \\\\(16\\\\times16\\\\) region at the current scale.\\n\\n#### Step 2: rotation alignment\\nThe patch itself need not be physically rotated. Instead, each gradient orientation is measured relative to the keypoint orientation \\\\(\\\\theta\\\\):\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\phi' = \\\\phi - \\\\theta.\\n\\\\]\\n\\nThis gives rotation invariance at lower computational cost.\\n\\n#### Step 3: divide into 4x4 cells\\nThe support window is partitioned into\\n\\n\\\\[\\n4 \\\\times 4 = 16\\n\\\\]\\n\\nspatial cells.\\n\\n#### Step 4: 8-bin orientation histogram per cell\\nEach cell accumulates an 8-bin histogram of local gradient directions. Therefore the descriptor dimension is\\n\\n\\\\[\\n16 \\\\times 8 = 128.\\n\\\\]\\n\\n#### Step 5: Gaussian spatial weighting\\nSamples nearer the center receive larger weights. This reduces boundary sensitivity and makes the descriptor more stable under localization errors.\\n\\n#### Step 6: trilinear interpolation\\nEach sample contributes not only to one histogram bin. Instead, it is interpolated across:\\n\\n1. neighboring cell positions in \\\\(x\\\\),\\n2. neighboring cell positions in \\\\(y\\\\),\\n3. neighboring orientation bins.\\n\\nThis is **trilinear interpolation**. It greatly reduces aliasing caused by hard quantization.\\n\\n#### Step 7: normalization, truncation, renormalization\\nLet the raw descriptor vector be \\\\(\\\\mathbf v\\\\in\\\\mathbb R^{128}\\\\).\\n\\n1. First normalize:\\n   \\\\[\\n   \\\\mathbf v \\\\leftarrow \\\\frac{\\\\mathbf v}{\\\\|\\\\mathbf v\\\\|_2}.\\n   \\\\]\\n2. Clamp large components:\\n   \\\\[\\n   v_i \\\\leftarrow \\\\min(v_i,0.2).\\n   \\\\]\\n3. Normalize again:\\n   \\\\[\\n   \\\\mathbf v \\\\leftarrow \\\\frac{\\\\mathbf v}{\\\\|\\\\mathbf v\\\\|_2}.\\n   \\\\]\\n\\n#### Why these three steps matter\\n- the first normalization reduces sensitivity to illumination scale;\\n- clamping prevents a few large gradients from dominating the descriptor;\\n- the second normalization restores consistent scale after truncation.\\n\\nThis makes the descriptor robust to contrast change, local saturation, and mild non-linear illumination effects.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.9 Relationship between the provided code and the SIFT pipeline\\n\\nThe provided `sift.py` already lays out the complete algorithm structure:\\n\\n- `build_gaussian_pyramid(...)`\\n- `build_dog_pyramid(...)`\\n- `detect_dog_keypoints(...)`\\n- `compute_keypoint_orientation(...)`\\n- `compute_sift_descriptor(...)`\\n\\nIt also defines the output visualization in `main()`:\\n\\n```python\\ncv.imwrite(\\\"sift_keypoints_vis.png\\\", vis)\\n```\\n\\nwhere the script draws:\\n\\n- green circles for keypoint positions,\\n- red line segments for dominant orientations.\\n\\nSo once the TODO parts are completed and the script is run on an input image, the output image directly visualizes both detection and orientation assignment.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.10 Expected experiment procedure\\n\\nA concise experiment process is:\\n\\n1. prepare a grayscale test image;\\n2. run keypoint detection on the Gaussian/DoG pyramid;\\n3. assign orientations;\\n4. compute 128-D descriptors;\\n5. save the visualization of oriented keypoints.\\n\\nA command-line example consistent with the provided script is:\\n\\n```bash\\npython sift.py --image input.png\\n```\\n\\nThe terminal is expected to print:\\n\\n- number of detected keypoints,\\n- number of oriented keypoints,\\n- descriptor array shape/content,\\n- saved file name `sift_keypoints_vis.png`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.11 Result presentation and analysis\\n\\nIf the implementation is correct, the visualization should show the following behavior:\\n\\n#### (1) Keypoints gather around distinctive structures\\nSIFT prefers:\\n- corners,\\n- blobs,\\n- textured junctions,\\n- high-information local patterns.\\n\\nIt usually suppresses:\\n- flat regions,\\n- noisy weak areas,\\n- long unstable edges.\\n\\n#### (2) Orientation arrows follow local dominant gradients\\nIn corners or textured patches, the orientation arrows should align with the strongest local pattern. If a location has multiple strong directions, several arrows may emerge from nearly the same point.\\n\\n#### (3) Multi-scale behavior\\nLarge structures should produce keypoints at coarser scales, while fine textures appear at smaller scales. This is the basis of scale invariance.\\n\\n#### (4) Descriptor stability\\nAlthough the descriptor itself is not directly visible, its design should make matching stable under:\\n- image rotation,\\n- moderate scaling,\\n- moderate lighting variation,\\n- small viewpoint or localization perturbations.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.12 Suggested figure placement\\n\\nIf the implementation is executed and produces the visualization, it can be inserted into the report as follows:\\n\\n```markdown\\n![SIFT Keypoints](sift_keypoints_vis.png)\\n```\\n\\nRecommended accompanying caption:\\n\\n> Figure: Oriented SIFT keypoints detected by the implemented pipeline. Green dots indicate keypoint locations, and red segments indicate assigned dominant orientations.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.13 Discussion of implementation details and possible failure modes\\n\\nEven when the algorithmic design is correct, several engineering details strongly affect the result quality.\\n\\n#### (1) Boundary handling\\nKeypoints too close to the image border cannot support a full orientation or descriptor window. They should be skipped, otherwise descriptors become incomplete or noisy.\\n\\n#### (2) Scale bookkeeping across octaves\\nWhen an octave is downsampled, keypoint coordinates in that octave are expressed in the smaller image. If final coordinates are reported in the original image system, they must be scaled back appropriately.\\n\\n#### (3) Gradient discretization\\nOrientation histograms are sensitive to the way gradients are computed. Using Sobel filters, as done in the skeleton, is a practical and reasonable choice.\\n\\n#### (4) Hard assignment vs interpolation\\nWithout spatial/orientation interpolation, descriptors become unstable. Trilinear interpolation is one of the most important details that distinguish a robust SIFT descriptor from a naive histogram descriptor.\\n\\n#### (5) Threshold choice\\n- too high contrast threshold: too few keypoints;\\n- too low contrast threshold: noisy detections;\\n- too strict edge suppression: some useful elongated structures are discarded;\\n- too loose edge suppression: many unstable edge points remain.\\n\\nSo parameter tuning affects the trade-off between quantity and stability.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.14 Advantages and limitations of SIFT\\n\\n#### Advantages\\n1. strong scale invariance through scale-space extrema;\\n2. strong rotation invariance through dominant orientation alignment;\\n3. good robustness to illumination changes through normalized histograms;\\n4. excellent distinctiveness due to the 128-D descriptor.\\n\\n#### Limitations\\n1. computation is heavier than very lightweight corner detectors;\\n2. descriptor dimensionality is relatively high;\\n3. under extreme viewpoint/projective distortion, performance can still degrade;\\n4. repetitive textures may still produce ambiguous matches.\\n\\nEven so, SIFT remains a landmark local-feature method and a standard baseline in computer vision.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2.15 Programming assignment summary\\n\\nThe implemented SIFT pipeline can be summarized as follows:\\n\\n1. Build Gaussian scale space.\\n2. Form DoG by subtracting adjacent Gaussian images.\\n3. Detect 3x3x3 local extrema across space and scale.\\n4. Remove unstable points using contrast threshold and Hessian edge suppression.\\n5. Assign one or more dominant orientations using a smoothed 36-bin histogram and sub-bin interpolation.\\n6. Construct a 128-D descriptor from a rotation-aligned 16x16 neighborhood with trilinear interpolation.\\n7. Normalize, clamp, and renormalize to improve illumination robustness.\\n\\nThis design explains why SIFT is simultaneously scale-invariant, rotation-invariant, and reasonably robust to photometric variation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Overall Conclusion\\n\\nThis homework combines projective geometry theory with feature extraction practice.\\n\\nFrom the theoretical side, perspective projection explains why:\\n- circles parallel to the image plane remain circles,\\n- parallel lines converge to vanishing points,\\n- all vanishing points of directions on one plane lie on a common vanishing line.\\n\\nFrom the programming side, SIFT demonstrates how geometric and photometric robustness can be achieved algorithmically using:\\n- scale-space extrema,\\n- orientation normalization,\\n- histogram-based local descriptors.\\n\\nThese two parts are closely related. Projective geometry explains how images are formed; SIFT addresses how to identify reliable structures in those images despite changes in scale, orientation, and imaging conditions. Together, they form a strong foundation for image matching, 3D reconstruction, and geometric computer vision.\\n\"}"
